<Pillar
  title="I Just Got Non-Renewed"
  description="What to do in the first 72 hours after a homeowners insurance non-renewal letter."
  intro="If you opened the mail today and your insurer is dropping you, start here. The pages in this section walk through what the letter actually means and what to do — in what order — before your coverage ends."
>
  <h2>Where to start</h2>
  <p>Two things are true at once: the clock is real, and you have more time than the letter makes it feel like. A non-renewal (your insurer declining to offer a new policy when the current one ends — different from a mid-policy cancellation) is almost always a portfolio decision about your ZIP code or roof age, not a judgment about you. Most states require 30 to 90 days of notice, and your coverage stays fully in force until the expiration date on the letter.</p>
  <p>Start with <a href="/non-renewed/what-a-non-renewal-letter-actually-means/">what the letter actually means</a> — it decodes the dates, the stated reason, and what your insurer is still obligated to do. Then work through the <a href="/non-renewed/your-30-60-90-day-decision-tree/">30-60-90 day decision tree</a>, which sequences every step from first phone call to bound replacement coverage.</p>
  <p>The other pages handle the specific worries that come up along the way: whether your lender can demand the loan back (short answer: technically yes, almost never happens), and what you are actually buying if the only quote you can get is from a surplus lines carrier. One rule above all the others: do not let coverage lapse, even for a day. An imperfect policy that starts the morning your old one ends beats a perfect policy three weeks late.</p>

